<details>
<summary>Edit: this is the original post</summary>

Turns out there is a question of what cases should this be optimized for?
_Edit_: Potentially worth it to add special cases for a few more elements.  
_Edit2_: I may have answered my own question in next post.

Case: Array contains no zero elements at end => equal between Current and proposed.
Case: Array contains between 1 and 3 zero elements at end => Current is faster.
Case: Array contains 4 zero elements at end => equal between Current and proposed.
Case: Array contains 5 or more zero elements at end => proposed is faster (increasing advantage with more zero elements).

"proposed" in previous paragraph benchmarked as "SpanIndexOfOpt" (using `LastIndexOfAnyExcept` with a special case for "last element is not zero").  
Proposed matches performance when nothing should change (assumed most common case).  
Sacrifice ~1ns and decreasing on low number of zeroes (assumed common).  
Gain ever more on higher number of zeroes (assumed ever decreasing probability).  
_Note_: I don't have a solid basis for how common the cases are. I generally assume 0 is more common than 1, which is more common than 2, and so on.

Methods benchmarked:
``` csharp
    // Benchmarked as "Current"
    public static int Current(uint[] val)
    {
        int len = val.Length - 1;
        while (len >= 0 && val[len] == 0) len--;
        len++;
        return len;
    }
    // Benchmarked as "SpanIndexOf"
    public static int UsingLastIndexOfAnyExcept(uint[] val)
    {
        int len = val.AsSpan().LastIndexOfAnyExcept((uint)0);
        len++;
        return len;
    }
    // Benchmarked as "SpanIndexOfOpt"
    public static int UsingLastIndexOfAnyExcept_WithOptimizedNoZeroes(uint[] val)
    {
        int len = val.Length;
        if (val[len - 1] == 0)
        {
            len = val.AsSpan().LastIndexOfAnyExcept((uint)0);
            len++;
        }
        return len;
    }
```
</details>

