@tannergooding One can argue that the floating-point zero is not the same as mathematical zero, but a 'directed' version of it, so that, for example `sqrt(-1+0i) == i` and `sqrt(-1-0i) == -i`. There's an interesting paper by William Kahan, "Much ado about nothing's sign bit" (https://people.freebsd.org/~das/kahan86branch.pdf) about the role of negative zero in complex computer arithmetic.

From this point of view, multiplying by a real number is not quite the same as multiplying by the real number with zero imaginary part. The difference comes down to whether you simplify before or after you convert standard math to floating-point math. Both options have reasonable arguments for and against.

Many languages simplify first: Fortran, C, Julia...

The choice you are making here is that multiplication by a real number must be exactly like multiplication by the real number converted to a complex number. I'm fine with that choice, but this should be made explicit in the documentation.

You are still going to get some surprises. The biggest is that there are special methods for real arguments _but they don't do anything special_, i.e. they are basically redundant. Another is that it's not always true that `1 * x == x`, for example when `x = 1 + inf*i`.

I also don't see why that cannot be made explicit in the implementation as well:

```csharp
public static Complex operator *(Complex left, double right)
{
    return left * (Complex)right;
}
```

I doubt if a hand-crafted version can be meaningfully faster.

In general, it would be very useful to have **a clear policy on numerical reproducibility**. With the explosion of platforms and platform-specific implementations (including different SIMD versions) that may even depend on memory alignment, this is even more important.

Making reproducibility guarantees can come at a significant cost: you usually have to settle for the slowest common denominator. Whether that cost is worth it depends on the application. The relatively few cases where it is shouldn't negatively impact the majority of cases where it doesn't matter if the last bit of `log(1.7374296064433465668e204` is rounded correctly.

