### Background and motivation

Inspired by this discussion:
https://discord.com/channels/143867839282020352/169726586931773440/1278024117202718913

There doesn't appear to be any way to determine if a type `T where T: INumber<T>` is an integer type or a real/float type.  There's `INumberBase.IsInteger`, but that works on values, not types.  It's not possible to try an `is` cast to `IBinaryInteger<T>` or `IFloatingPoint<T>` because it won't compile, as `T` is not known to satisfy the necessary type constraints at compile-time.

### API Proposal

There should be a way to answer this question.  There are two obvious solutions: by methods, or by marker interfaces.

## Methods:
Add to `INumberBase<TSelf>`:

```
        /// <summary>Returns true if this type is any type of integer.</summary>
        static abstract bool IsIntegerType { get; }

        /// <summary>Returns true if this type is any type of number that supports a decimal point.</summary>
        static abstract bool IsFloatType { get; }
```
With corresponding implementations on the various existing types.

-----

## Marker Interfaces:
Add to IBinaryInteger.cs:
```
+     public interface IBinaryInteger
+     { }
     /// <summary>Defines an integer type that is represented in a base-2 format.</summary>
     /// <typeparam name="TSelf">The type that implements the interface.</typeparam>
     public interface IBinaryInteger<TSelf>
          : IBinaryNumber<TSelf>,
-           IShiftOperators<TSelf, int, TSelf>
+           IShiftOperators<TSelf, int, TSelf>,
+           IBinaryInteger
         where TSelf : IBinaryInteger<TSelf>?
```

Add to IFloatingPoint.cs:
```
+     public interface IFloatingPoint
+     { }
     /// <summary>Defines a floating-point type.</summary>
     /// <typeparam name="TSelf">The type that implements the interface.</typeparam>
     public interface IFloatingPoint<TSelf>
         : IFloatingPointConstants<TSelf>,
           INumber<TSelf>,
-          ISignedNumber<TSelf>
+          ISignedNumber<TSelf>,
+          IFloatingPoint 
        where TSelf : IFloatingPoint<TSelf>?
```


### API Usage

## Methods:
```
void TypeTester<T>(T value) where T: INumberBase<T>
{
   if (T.IsInteger)  //ideally the JIT would be aware of this during code generation
   {
      DoSomething();
   }
   else
   {
      DoSomethingElse();
   }
}
```
-----
## Marker interfaces:
```
void TypeTester<T>(T value) where T: INumberBase<T>
{
   if (value is IBinaryInteger)  //ideally the JIT would be aware of this during code generation
   {
      DoSomething();
   }
   else
   {
      DoSomethingElse();
   }
}
```


### Alternative Designs

If https://github.com/dotnet/csharplang/discussions/6308 were to be implemented, it would cover this problem without requiring API changes.

### Risks

The method solution would work well and be very discoverable, but would be a breaking change to any existing third-party types that implement `INumberBase`.  The marker interface solution, on the other hand, would not break backwards compatibility, but it would be less discoverable and (maybe?) more difficult for the JIT to optimize.

