### Background and motivation

`BigMul` is useful for performing large multiplications (e.g., 64x64->128, 32x32->64, etc.), but there is currently no way to do it generically. You can use this to detect overflow without throwing & how much by, you can use it to write larger integral types generically, etc.

`MultiplyHigh` is useful for things like fixed point division - it is the high part of `BigMul`, e.g.,
```csharp
uint x = ...;
var divBy3 = x / 3; // same as `MultiplyHigh(x, 0xAAAAAAABu) >> 1`, which is what the JIT will emit
```
but there is also no way to do this generically. Ideally you can pre-compute the constant for your dynamic division factor & then use it for division in generic algorithms.
Background: https://rubenvannieuwpoort.nl/posts/division-by-constant-unsigned-integers

`MultiplyLow` is corresponding the low part of `BigMul` - for fixed sized types, it would be the same as `a * b`, for `BigInteger` it would instead be the low `max(left.bits, right.bits)` bits, as this works best for most uses of the APIs, e.g., fixed point division & allows for reduced allocations, etc.

### API Proposal

```csharp
namespace System.Numerics
{
    public interface IBinaryInteger<TSelf>
    {
        static virtual (TSelf High, TSelf Low) BigMul(TSelf left, TSelf right)
        {
            // We cannot really implement this properly in general using existing APIs afaict (although, I suppose we could do it bit-by-bit & make it correct), so just make it work for fixed integer sized types in cases where it doesn't overflow
            TSelf result = checked(left * right);
            return (IsNegative(result) ? ~TSelf.Zero : TSelf.Zero, result);
        }

        // If we have a good BigMul, we can implement MultiplyHigh & MultiplyLow correctly
        static virtual TSelf MultiplyHigh(TSelf left, TSelf right) => BigMul(left, right).High;
        static virtual TSelf MultiplyLow(TSelf left, TSelf right) => BigMul(left, right).Low;
    }

    public static class Vector
    {
        public static (Vector<T> High, Vector<T> Low) BigMul<T>(Vector<T> left, Vector<T> right) where T : IBinaryInteger<T>;
        public static Vector<T> MultiplyHigh<T>(Vector<T> left, Vector<T> right) where T : IBinaryInteger<T>;
        // MultiplyLow is not necessary as it works the same as * on fixed sized integer types, which are the only relevant supported element types for `Vector<T>`
    }

    public readonly struct BigInteger
    {
        // low has the bottom max(left.bits, right.bits) bits, and high has all the bits above that
        public static BigInteger MultiplyHigh(BigInteger left, BigInteger right) => ...;
        public static BigInteger MultiplyLow(BigInteger left, BigInteger right) => ...;
        public static static (BigInteger High, BigInteger Low) BigMul(BigInteger left, BigInteger right) => ...;
    }
}

namespace System
{
    public readonly struct Byte/Char/Int128/Int16/Int32/Int64/IntPtr/SByte/UInt128/UInt16/UInt32/UInt64/UIntPtr
    {
        public static TSelf MultiplyHigh(TSelf left, TSelf right) => ...;
        static (TSelf High, TSelf Low) IBinaryInteger<TSelf>.BigMul(TSelf left, TSelf right) => ...;
        static TSelf IBinaryInteger<TSelf>.MultiplyLow(TSelf left, TSelf right) => left * right;
    }
}

namespace System.Runtime.Intrinsics
{
    public static class Vector64
    {
        public static (Vector64<T> High, Vector64<T> Low) BigMul<T>(Vector64<T> left, Vector64<T> right) where T : IBinaryInteger<T>;
        public static Vector64<T> MultiplyHigh<T>(Vector64<T> left, Vector64<T> right) where T : IBinaryInteger<T>;
        // MultiplyLow is not necessary as it works the same as * on fixed sized integer types, which are the only relevant supported element types for `Vector64<T>`
    }

    public static class Vector128
    {
        public static (Vector128<T> High, Vector128<T> Low) BigMul<T>(Vector128<T> left, Vector128<T> right) where T : IBinaryInteger<T>;
        public static Vector128<T> MultiplyHigh<T>(Vector128<T> left, Vector128<T> right) where T : IBinaryInteger<T>;
